{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2239f6de-3c61-411e-818d-8d4a70c2f3d4","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace (e.g., 30 seconds):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** — open the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app). To convert for PerfView:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** with the SDK image or use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar for always-on diagnostics.\n- For **host-level** collection with admin access, you can also run `PerfView.exe` on the node, but container-internal `dotnet-trace` is usually simpler and sufficient.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"383a1293-2406-476a-802a-2f921773806b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":439},"id":"881c85ce-c4ed-4648-b745-5d19056920ed","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:49:24.215Z","parentId":"77a3cede-43c4-4e02-a3ad-ba6d8d9ee401"}
